1. Overview

Dancing is a "Very Easy" Windows-based machine designed to introduce the SMB protocol. Unlike the previous machines (Meow and Fawn) which focused on Telnet and FTP, this lab demonstrates how Windows environments often share files and resources across a network.
2. Enumeration
2.1. Initial Scan

The process began with an Nmap scan to identify open ports and the services running on the target.

    Command: nmap -sV -p 445 <Target_IP>

    Result: Port 445/tcp was identified as open, running a Microsoft Windows SMB service.

2.2. Identifying Toolset

To interact with the SMB service, the smbclient utility was used. To view the help menu and available flags for this tool before connecting, the following command was referenced:

    Command: smbclient -? (or -h)

2.3. Listing Shares

Before attempting to log in, it was necessary to list the available shares on the host to find a point of entry.

    Command: smbclient -L <Target_IP>

    Discovery: The scan revealed four shares: ADMIN$, C$, IPC$, and WorkShares.

3. Exploitation
3.1. Anonymous Authentication

The custom share, WorkShares, appeared to be a non-standard directory, suggesting a higher likelihood of misconfiguration. An attempt was made to connect without valid credentials (Anonymous Login).

    Connection Command: smbclient //<Target_IP>/WorkShares

    Password Prompt: When prompted, the field was left blank and Enter was pressed.

    Access: The server accepted the empty password, providing an interactive smb: \> prompt.

3.2. File Navigation and Exfiltration

Standard directory navigation commands were used to locate the flag within the remote filesystem.

    ls: Listed two directories: Amy.J and James.P.

    cd James.P: Navigated into the folder for user James.

    ls: Confirmed the existence of flag.txt.

    get flag.txt: Downloaded the flag file to the local Kali machine.

    cd ..: Used to move back up the directory tree during navigation.

